A '''prestige picture''' is a [[film]] produced to bolster the [[film studio]]'s perceived artistic integrity, rather than to turn a large profit;<ref>{{cite journal |date=16 August 1937 |title=Cinema: Prestige Picture |journal=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,770806,00.html |access-date=2017-02-05}}</ref> the studio may even expect the film to lose money.<ref name="Harmetz">{{cite book |last=Harmetz |first=Aljean |year=2013 |title=The Making of The Wizard of Oz |page=19 |publisher=Chicago Review Press |chapter=The Studio, 1938 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nSFQAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA19 |location=Chicago |isbn=978-1-61374-832-9 |oclc=837180455 |access-date=2017-02-05}}</ref>
Prestige pictures are largely the province of major [[Cinema of the United States|Hollywood]] film studios—such as [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] and [[Warner Bros.]]—that produce numerous films every year. In the 1930s, such studios might release one prestige picture per year.<ref name="Harmetz" /> The films' [[screenwriter]]s drew material from historical events, well-known literary classics, or popular novels or plays.<ref>{{cite book |title=History of the American Cinema, Volume 5: Grand Design—Hollywood as a Modern Business Enterprise, 1930–1939 |last=Balio |first=Tino |publisher=University of California Press |location=Berkeley |page=179 |chapter=Production Trends |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_J9HTLOI08wC&pg=PA179 |isbn=0-520-20334-8 |oclc=32738211 |year=1995 |access-date=2017-02-05}}</ref>
In many cases, Hollywood film studios have enlisted British actors and directors for the production of prestige films.<ref>{{cite book |last=Giannetti |first=Louis D. |year=1981 |title=Masters of the American Cinema |publisher=Prentice-Hall |location=Englewood Cliffs |page=213 |oclc=7197462}}</ref> One producer of prestige pictures within [[Cinema of the United Kingdom|the United Kingdom's own film industry]] was [[Alexander Korda]] (1893–1956).<ref>{{cite book |editor-last=Holland |editor-first=Peter |last=Jackson |first=Russell |title=Shakespeare, Memory and Performance |page=247 |chapter=Remembering Bergner's Rosalind |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Xj9351zeLFIC&pg=PA247 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=2006 |isbn=978-0-521-86380-3 |oclc=70883148 |access-date=2017-02-05}}</ref>
